A unprecedented future
JERUSALEM – At my almost 90 years of age, I cannot remember a time when the past was so insignificant for political decision-making.
None of the significant developments of the present were predicted by anyone beforehand.
Experts did examine the past, but due to their confinement in old paradigms, they could not derive the future from it.
Due to the dynamic complexity of the world today, where, in light of a scientifically grounded and rapidly changing global economy, even more events are dependent on one another, we are unable to predict the future based on a linear extrapolation of the past.
The only certainty is that the future will be determined by scientific progress and innovation, which cannot be known in advance.
As a result of these developments, the traditional power of states and state leaders is decreasing. In today's globalized economy, it is not politicians but innovators who exert the greatest influence.
The globalized economy affects all states, yet no single state can determine the outcome, because science and technology are borderless.
Global operating companies want to conduct their business all over the world, which, on the one hand, suffers the sovereignty, but on the other hand, weakens racism and prejudices, as well as nationalism to a significant extent.
Due to this change, the affairs of this world are now in the hands of a younger generation. They are more technologically advanced than their parents and are connected to each other through social networks that overcome national borders, language barriers, or different forms of government.
The young founders of Facebook and Google exert greater global influence than many heads of state and generals.
These young people also form the vanguard of emerging political protest movements.
The "Arab Spring", the tent demonstrations in Israel, Occupy Wall Street, and the protests in Russia mark not a clash of cultures, but a battle of generations.
The young generation knows that the way states and economies are currently run is unsuitable for the new times.
However, there are political "free riders" who want to exploit this latest awakening. But not by advancing an agenda of freedom, but by introducing new forms of coercion.
In the Arab world, Islamist extremists are mainly taking over the protests of the young generation and stealing their revolution.
Israel has positively reacted to the will of the young generation, but it cannot and should not intervene in the events of the Arab world.
We are at heart with the rebellious young people and their legitimate desire for freedom and basic rights that should enable them to be heard, choose their political leadership, and sustain their livelihood.
The Israelis are waiting for the day when their country will no longer be the only democracy in the region, because the existence as an island of prosperity in the midst of a sea of poverty is unnatural.
However, there is a serious concern that the politically well-organized extremists will try to win control over less well-organized liberals in elections and thus prevent peace and stability.
Radical fundamentalists cannot offer real solutions to the fundamental problems of the region.
The current social upheavals threaten their way of life, which includes the discrimination of women and a ban on modern education.
However, only fundamental reforms of established authority can pave the way towards freedom and growth.
Israel can serve as an example for others to achieve economic prosperity and social freedom, because its success is justified by the fact that the country started with almost nothing.
When we returned home, we were rich in history, but poor in natural resources.
We could only rely on our human capital.
Therefore, we invested in education and science. That's why we now have the highest percentage of scientists and patents per capita.
About 95 percent of our agriculture is based on high technology.
We consume less water and still have higher crop yields per square meter of arable land than any other country in the world.
What Israel has achieved can also be accomplished by others.
We are happy to offer our help wherever it is desired.
Together and in peace with our neighbors, we can shape a region of hope, development, and success.
Above all, we must do everything in our power to bring an end to the conflict with the Palestinians.
Israel was not created to rule over another people, and this is not Israel's destiny.
We are genuinely interested in creating a Palestinian state that exists peacefully and side by side with Israel - the democratic state of the Jewish people.
For us, peace is both a moral imperative and a national security strategy, because solving the conflict would help stabilize the region by neutralizing extremists who aim to manipulate civil movements to advance their radical agenda.
The international community can support these efforts by offering incentives to countries striving for freedom and progress.
At the same time, decisive and pioneering political measures must be taken against the extremists.
The Iran is a source of moral decay, where extremism is promoted and reforms are blocked. It crushes legitimate protests of its own citizens and works against the brave Syrians who are currently fighting for their freedom.
The Iran also employs several proxies to carry out terrorism against moderate forces in the Palestinian Authority, Lebanon, and Iraq.
If Iran succeeds in acquiring nuclear weapons, its leaders could shake the Middle East and North Africa and further fuel extremism and violence.
Israel will defend itself if Iran continues to demand the destruction of Israel.
But Israel is not the only one threatened. Iran is a danger to peace and stability all around the world.
The democracies of this world have declared that they will not allow Iran to acquire nuclear weapons. It is their duty to uphold this commitment before it is too late.
Beyond these short-term challenges, we all have a duty to fundamentally change the way we prepare our children to deal with the world of today.
At a time when the past has become irrelevant for predicting the future, education must provide all children with the opportunity to unleash their potential.
The teachers of today should motivate our children to creativity and innovation.
Self-expression is just as important as free speech.
I am writing this article at the age of 88, but not because I have learned from experience.
On the contrary: experience is overvalued and often restricts the courage needed to face the future and create an unprecedented new world.
The future is already here. Looking back makes no sense.
